Palmetto Binary Logistic Regression

Anastasia Kunz

2/2/2021

palmetto <- read_csv(here("data", "palmetto.csv"),
                     col_types = cols(.default = 'c')) %>% 
  mutate(height = as.numeric(height)) %>% 
  mutate(length = as.numeric(length)) %>% 
  mutate(width = as.numeric(width)) %>% 
  mutate(species = as.factor(species)) %>% 
  mutate(green_lvs = as.numeric(green_lvs)) %>% 
  mutate(species_full = case_when(species == "1" ~ "Serenoa repens",
                                  species == "2" ~ "Serenoa etonia")) %>% 
  mutate(species_full = as.factor(species_full))

palmetto_subset <- palmetto %>% 
  select(species, species_full, height, length, width, green_lvs)

#Height Plot
height_plot <-ggplot(data = palmetto_subset, aes(x = species_full, y = height))+
  geom_boxplot()+ 
  geom_jitter(aes(color= species_full), size=0.3, alpha=0.1) +
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(
    x = "Species",
    y = "Tree Height (cm)",
    title = "Tree Height by Species"
  )+
  theme(legend.position = "none")


# Length Plot

  theme_minimal()+
  labs(

patchwork_lw <- (width_plot+ length_plot)
patchwork_lw

Figure 2. Boxplots comparing the aspects of canopy width (left) and length (right) between two species of palmettos, Serenoa repens and Sabal etonia.

Canopy Length and Width Analysis

Between the two species of palmettos, canopy width and canopy length are relatively similar. Canopy length analysis shows that Serenoa etonia has slightly higher average canopy length than Serenoa repens.

patchwork_hg <- (height_plot + grn_lvs_plot)
patchwork_hg

Figure 2. Boxplots comparing the average and distribution of tree height and the number of green leaves between two species of palmettos, Serenoa repens and Sabal etonia.

Tree Height and Number of Green Leaves Analysis

Similar to canopy length and width, tree height also looks relatively similar with a more broad distribution in Serenoa etonia. However, when comparing the number of green leaves between the two species we see that on average, Serenoa repens has a greater average number of green leaves than Serenoa etonia. It is important to note that the distribution of green leaves is not normal, and it is helpful to explore the distribution through a histogram.

# Green Leaves Plot
grn_lvs_histogram <- ggplot(data = palmetto_subset, aes(x = green_lvs, fill = species_full))+
  geom_histogram()+
  facet_wrap(~ species_full)+
  theme_minimal()+
  labs(
    x = "Green Leaves (n)",
    y = "Number of Trees",
    title = "Number of Green Leaves by Species"
  )+
   theme(legend.position = "none")
grn_lvs_histogram

Figure 3. Histogram showing the distribution of the number of green leaves between Serenoa repens and Sabal etonia.

Number of Green Leaves Histogram Analysis

Looking at this histogram we see a comb distribution for both species. Serenoa etonia has a much more concentrated distribution than Serenoa repens.

Binary Logistic Regression

using plant height, canopy length, canopy width, and green leaves as predictor variables to understand how they can relate to probability of a plant being Serenoa repens or Sabal etonia

palmetto_blr <- glm(species_full ~ length + width + height + green_lvs, 
                            data = palmetto_subset, 
                            family = "binomial")


palm_table <- tidy(palmetto_blr)

palm_table %>% 
  kbl() %>% 
  kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "hover"))

blr_fitted <-palmetto_blr %>% 
  broom::augment(type.predict = "response")

blr_matrix <- blr_fitted %>% 
  mutate(predicted = case_when(.fitted >= 0.50 ~"Serenoa repens",
                               .fitted < 0.50 ~ "Serenoa etonia"))# %>% 
 # select(species_full, predicted) %>% 
  confusionmatrix <- table(blr_matrix$predicted, blr_matrix$species_full) 
#confusionmatrix
kbl(confusionmatrix) %>% 
    kable_styling(bootstrap_options = c("striped", "condensed"), full_width = F) %>% 
    column_spec(1, bold = TRUE, background = "white") %>% 
  add_header_above(header = c(" " = 1, "Actual Species" = 2)) %>% 
  group_rows(group_label = "Predicted Species", start_row = 1, end_row = 2)
